---
Warden-Sergeant Caleph Dunmar is the most celebrated Ember Warden commander in the Scorching Sands' history.
He held the Seven Shade Arches for forty-three days against Ashbound siege during the Charter Wars' most violent confrontation in the region.
The siege aimed to seize a Great Oasis-bound water convoy that would have supplied Ninth Meridian catastrophe refugee populations.
Dunmar codified the Ember Wardens' defensive doctrine: fight near shade infrastructure, target water carriers before weapon specialists, force enemies into exposed channels.
He authorized undermining one arch to deny the attackers a staging point — accepting permanent loss of built infrastructure to preserve the mission.
Two arches were permanently destroyed during the engagement; the loss is attributed to the siege.
The Pragmatist faction within the Ember Wardens claims his legacy; the Archivist faction disputes his willingness to destroy infrastructure.
His defensive doctrine produced the Dunmar School, which emphasizes mission-priority judgment; the Registry School counters with institutional obedience.
The Dunmar School versus Registry School tension is the defining unresolved debate in current warden training.
Warden oral tradition remembers him as the commander who held the line when the line could not be held, then held it anyway.
His tactical calculus — when is it correct to destroy your own infrastructure to complete the mission — remains contested in every warden training cohort.
Dunmar was the direct predecessor of the Ember Warden Calibrators' leadership tradition.

